const Q_CRK_2011=[{"id": "objective>CRK>2011>1", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God blessed and hallowed the seventh day because</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">it was the day He rested from creation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">it was the day He created man</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He wanted it to be a day of worship</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He saw that all He had created was good </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to the Bible, specifically Genesis 2:2-3, God blessed the seventh day and made it holy because on it He rested from all the work of creating that He had done. Therefore, the correct answer is that God blessed and hallowed the seventh day because it was the day He rested from creation.</div>", "topic": "THE SOVEREIGNTY OF GOD :GOD AS CREATOR AND CONTROLLER OF THE UNIVERSE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>2", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Noah's ark was sustained during the flood by its</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">resting on the highest mountains </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">being rowed on the waters </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">floating on the water</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">being anchored safely</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Bible, specifically Genesis 7:17-18, states that the ark was lifted high above the earth as the waters rose and increased greatly on the earth, and the ark floated on the surface of the water. Therefore, Noah's ark was sustained during the flood by its floating on the water.</div>", "topic": "THE COVENANT : THE FLOOD AND GOD'S COVENANT WITH NOAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>3", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God visited the children of Isreal on Mount Sinai during the giving of the commandments through</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a storm</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">mist and dew</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">smoke and fire</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a still small voice</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Exodus, it is recorded that when God gave the Ten Commandments to the Israelites at Mount Sinai, His presence was manifested through smoke and fire. This is found in Exodus 19:18 which says, 'Mount Sinai was covered with smoke, because the Lord descended on it in fire. The smoke billowed up from it like smoke from a furnace, and the whole mountain trembled violently.' Therefore, the correct answer is 'smoke and fire'.</div>", "topic": "THE COVENANT : GOD'S COVENANT WITH ISRAEL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>4", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When asked to interpret Pharaoh's dream, Joseph's first response was</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"...God has revealed to Pharaoh what he is about to do.\" </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"It is not in me; God will give Pharaoh a favourable answer. \"</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"... God  will shortly bring it to pass.\"</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"...let Pharaoh select a man discrete and wise.\"</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Genesis 41:16, when Pharaoh asked Joseph to interpret his dream, Joseph's first response was, 'I cannot do it,' Joseph replied to Pharaoh, 'but God will give Pharaoh the answer he desires.' This is similar to the option 'It is not in me; God will give Pharaoh a favourable answer.' Therefore, the correct answer is this option.</div>", "topic": "LEADERSHIP QUALITIES : JOSEPH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>5", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When Joshua fell upon his face during Israel's defeat to Ai, God told him to rise and </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">send more courageous soldiers to Ai</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">encourage the people </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pray fervently against their enemies</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sanctify the people</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, after the defeat of Israel by Ai, Joshua fell on his face in despair. God told him to rise and sanctify the people (Joshua 7:13). Sanctify in this context means to purify or make holy. The Israelites had sinned by taking the accursed things from Jericho, which was against God's command. Therefore, sanctification was necessary for them to be able to stand before their enemies.</div>", "topic": "LEADERSHIP QUALITIES : JOSHUA"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>6", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God guided Abraham's steward in choosing a wife for Isaac by </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">teaching him how to select a good woman </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">leading a lady to fulfil his prayer request</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">taking him to Abraham's fatherland</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">giving him an exemplary woman</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Genesis 24, Abraham's servant prayed to God for guidance in choosing a wife for Isaac. He asked that the woman who would offer him and his camels water to drink would be the one chosen for Isaac. Rebecca fulfilled this prayer request, thus God guided Abraham's servant by leading a lady to fulfil his prayer request.</div>", "topic": "THE COVENANT : GOD'S COVENANT WITH ABRAHAM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>7", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Why was God angry with Eli?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Eli's sons disregarded the people's warning </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Eli's sons were wicked people</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Eli's sons dishonoured God and he treated them with levity</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Eli's sons were appointed as priests against God's will</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, specifically in the book of 1 Samuel 2:12-17, 22-25, Eli's sons, Hophni and Phinehas, were described as wicked men who had no regard for the Lord or for the duties of the priests to the people. They were taking portions of the sacrifices that were not theirs to take and sleeping with the women who served at the entrance to the Tent of Meeting. When Eli heard about their behavior, he rebuked them but did not take any further action to stop them. God was angry with Eli because he honored his sons more than he honored God. Eli knew about their sins but failed to restrain them. This is why God's judgment came upon Eli's house (1 Samuel 2:27-36).</div>", "topic": "PARENTAL RESPONSIBILITY : ELI AND SAMUEL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>8", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Laxity in disciplining children is dangerous to both the family and society as exemplified by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jonathan</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Tamar</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Absalom</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ahikam</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Absalom, the third son of David, is an example of the danger of laxity in disciplining children. Absalom killed his half-brother Amnon for raping their sister Tamar (2 Samuel 13). Later, he conspired against his father, David, and temporarily overthrew him (2 Samuel 15-18). David, out of love for Absalom, failed to discipline him appropriately for his actions. This lack of discipline led to Absalom developing a rebellious and vengeful attitude, which eventually led to his downfall and death. This story serves as a warning of the potential societal and familial dangers of failing to discipline children.</div>", "topic": "PARENTAL RESPONSIBILITY : DAVID"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>9", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God promised Abraham that nations of the earth shall be blessed through him because</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he had obeyed Him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">his descendants had obeyed Him </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">of his kindness to Hagar</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">of his exemplary leadership</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God promised Abraham that nations of the earth shall be blessed through him because he had obeyed Him. This is a biblical concept found in Genesis 22:18, where God says 'In your seed all the nations of the earth shall be blessed, because you have obeyed My voice.' Therefore, the correct answer is option 1.</div>", "topic": "THE COVENANT : GOD'S COVENANT WITH ABRAHAM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>10", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The punishment for Adam and Eve's sin was that they</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">were driven out of the garden</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">would be naked forever</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">would never fellowship with God</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">would be enemies of crawling animals</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The punishment for Adam and Eve's sin was that they were driven out of the Garden of Eden. This is a biblical concept found in Genesis 3:23-24, where God sends them out of the garden to prevent them from eating from the tree of life. Therefore, the correct answer is option 1.</div>", "topic": "OBEDIENCE AND DISOBEDIENCE :EXAMPLES OF ADAM, COLLECTION OF MANNA, THE GOLDEN CALF, MOSES AND SAUL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>11", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Do not destroy him; for who can stretch out his hand on the LORD'S anointed and be guiltless?\" ' <br/> In the statement above, David was acknowledging God's role in </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Abishai's command</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Saul's leadership</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Samuel's priesthood </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Elijah's prophethood</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement was made by David when he had the opportunity to kill Saul but he didn't. He acknowledged that Saul was anointed by God and it was not his place to harm him. This shows his recognition of God's role in Saul's leadership.</div>", "topic": "A MAN AFER GOD'S OWN HEART: DAVID'S SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>12", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Saul's decision to consult a medium displayed his lack of </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">faith in his army </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">faith in God </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">leadership qualities</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">respect for the dead</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Saul's decision to consult a medium, which is against God's commandments, shows his lack of faith in God. If he had faith in God, he would have sought God's guidance instead of resorting to a medium.</div>", "topic": "DECISION-MAKING : RELIANCE ON A MEDIUM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>13", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Solomon made the most unwise decision by engaging in </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">marriages to foreign women </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">alliances with his brothers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">so many wars of conquest </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">developmental works</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Solomon's unwise decision was his marriages to foreign women. According to the Bible, Solomon married many foreign women (besides the daughter of Pharaoh), including Moabites, Ammonites, Edomites, Sidonians, and Hittites. They were from nations about which the LORD had told the Israelites, 'You must not intermarry with them, because they will surely turn your hearts after their gods.' Nevertheless, Solomon held fast to them in love (1 Kings 11:1-2). This led him to stray from God in his later years.</div>", "topic": "DECISION-MAKING : UNWISE POLICIES OF SOLOMON AND REHOBOAM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>14", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The man of God whose word was ignored by Kings Ahab and Jehoshaphat was</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Elijah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Zedekaih</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Malakiah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Micaiah</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The man of God whose word was ignored by Kings Ahab and Jehoshaphat was Micaiah. In 1 Kings 22, both kings ignored the prophecy of Micaiah who predicted a defeat in the battle at Ramoth-Gilead. Instead, they listened to the false prophets who predicted victory. This led to Ahab's death in the battle, just as Micaiah had prophesied.</div>", "topic": "CONCERN FOR JUDAH : CONDITION OF JUDAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>15", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Baal did not answer his worshippers at the contest on Mount Carmel because he</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">was annoyed with their sacrifice</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">did not hear</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wanted to disgrace his worshippers </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">was asleep</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the biblical account of the contest on Mount Carmel (1 Kings 18), the prophet Elijah challenged the prophets of Baal to call on their god to light a fire for a sacrifice. Despite their loud cries and rituals, Baal did not answer because he does not exist. Therefore, the correct answer is that Baal did not hear his worshippers.</div>", "topic": "THE SUPREMACY OF GOD : RELIGIOUS TENSION AND THE POWER OF GOD ON MOUNT CARMEL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>16", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The workmen who repaired the house of the Lord during Josiah's religious reforms were not made to account for the money given them because they </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">did not receive the money directly </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lacked accounting capabilities</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">bribed the Temple officials</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">were honest workmen</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the biblical account of King Josiah's religious reforms (2 Kings 22), it is stated that the workmen who repaired the house of the Lord were not required to account for the money given to them because they were considered honest. Therefore, the correct answer is that they were honest workmen.</div>", "topic": "RELIGIOUS REFORMS IN JUDAH : CLEANSING OF THE TEMPLE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>17", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">During Jehoakim's reign, Judah was destroyed as punishment for Manasseh's sin of </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">keeping Temple prostitutes in the land</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">defiling the vessels in the Temple</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">offering unacceptable sacrifice</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">shedding innocent blood</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">During Jehoakim's reign, Judah was destroyed as punishment for Manasseh's sin of shedding innocent blood. Manasseh was one of the kings of Judah who did evil in the sight of the Lord. He shed so much innocent blood that he filled Jerusalem from one end to another, besides his sin with which he made Judah sin, in doing what was evil in the sight of the Lord.</div>", "topic": "CONCERN FOR JUDAH : THE FALL OF JERUSALEM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>18", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nehemiah responded to the opposition of the enemies of Israel by </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">telling the people not to say a word</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">reporting the issue to King Artaxerxes</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">inviting them to dialogue in the King's court</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">asking God to return their taunt back to them</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nehemiah responded to the opposition of the enemies of Israel by asking God to return their taunt back to them. When Sanballat, Tobiah, the Arabs, the Ammonites, and the Ashdodites heard that the repair of the walls of Jerusalem was going forward and that the gaps were beginning to be closed, they were very angry. They all plotted together to come and fight against Jerusalem and to cause confusion in it. So Nehemiah prayed to God and set a guard as a protection against them day and night.</div>", "topic": "CONCERN FOR JUDAH : RESPONSE TO THE STATE OF JUDAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>19", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nebuchadnezzar ordered his subjects to worship the image he set up whenever they</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">heard his voice </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">saw him stand before the image</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">heard the sound of the horn</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">were told to do so</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, specifically in the book of Daniel 3:1-7, King Nebuchadnezzar made an image of gold and ordered that as soon as the people heard the sound of the horn, flute, zither, lyre, harp, pipe and all kinds of music, they must fall down and worship the image he had set up. Therefore, the correct answer is 'heard the sound of the horn'.</div>", "topic": "CONCERN FOR JUDAH : CONDITION OF JUDAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>20", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"What is this that you have done!\" <br/> The people in the ship asked Jonah the question above because</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he was fast asleep in the ship</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they knew he was fleeing from the LORD</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he lied to them about his presence in the ship</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they realised that he had made attempts to commit suicide</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, specifically in the book of Jonah 1:7-10, when the ship was caught in a storm, the sailors cast lots to find out who was responsible for the calamity. The lot fell on Jonah and they asked him about his identity and why this had happened. Jonah confessed that he was fleeing from the Lord, which is why they asked him 'What is this that you have done!'. Therefore, the correct answer is 'they knew he was fleeing from the LORD'.</div>", "topic": "GOD'S MESSAGE TO NINEVEH: JONAH AND HIS MESSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>21", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"What shall I do with you, O Ephraim? What shall I do with you, O Judah? Your love is like a morning cloud...\"  <br/> In the statement above the love of Israel is compared to a morning cloud because it </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">disappears fast </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">withers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">is cloudy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">darken the day</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the biblical context, the love of Israel is compared to a morning cloud because it disappears fast. Morning clouds often disappear as the day warms up, symbolizing the fleeting and inconsistent love of the Israelites.</div>", "topic": "CONCERN FOR JUDAH : CONDITION OF JUDAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>22", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Amos, God desires knowledge of Him rather than</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">fervent prayers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">dependency on the Law </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the multitude of prophecies </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">burnt offerings</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to the prophet Amos in the Bible, God desires knowledge of Him rather than burnt offerings. This is a critique of the Israelites' religious practices at the time, which focused more on ritual sacrifices (burnt offerings) than on truly knowing and following God's will.</div>", "topic": "SOCIAL JUSTICE, TRUE RELIGION AND DIVINE LOVE:SOCIAL JUSTICE AND TRUE RELIGION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>23", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In his vision, Isaiah's guilt was taken away and his sin forgiven after</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the angel of the LORD appeared to him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">his mouth was touched with a burning coal</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the seraphim had spoken to him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he had agreed to serve God</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Isaiah 6:6-7, it is written that one of the seraphim flew to Isaiah with a live coal in his hand, which he had taken with tongs from the altar. With it he touched Isaiah's mouth and said, 'See, this has touched your lips; your guilt is taken away and your sin atoned for.' Therefore, Isaiah's guilt was taken away and his sin forgiven after his mouth was touched with a burning coal.</div>", "topic": "HOLINESS AND DIVINE CALL : THE CALL OF ISAIAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>24", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The prophet who was ordained from the womb for God's service was</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jeremiah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Isaiah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ezekiel </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Hosea</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Jeremiah 1:5, God said to Jeremiah, 'Before I formed you in the womb I knew you, before you were born I set you apart; I appointed you as a prophet to the nations.' Therefore, Jeremiah was the prophet who was ordained from the womb for God's service.</div>", "topic": "HOLINESS AND DIVINE CALL : THE CALL OF JEREMIAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>25", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Jeremiah, the anger of God towards Israel would only be reduced by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">His mercy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the prophet's repentance</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the prophet's prayers</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">His glory</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to the book of Jeremiah, it is God's mercy that would reduce His anger towards Israel. This is based on the understanding that God's mercy is His willingness to forgive and not punish as much as the sin deserves.</div>", "topic": "CONCERN FOR JUDAH : RESPONSE TO THE STATE OF JUDAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>26", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When Zechariah saw the angel of the Lord standing on the right side of the altar of incense, he</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">cried out to him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">was troubled and afraid</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">rejoiced in the Lord</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">left the Temple immediately</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Luke 1:12, when Zechariah saw the angel of the Lord standing on the right side of the altar of incense, he was troubled and fear fell upon him. This was a common reaction in the Bible when humans encountered angels.</div>", "topic": "THE BIRTH AND EARLY LIFE OF JESUS : JOHN, THE FORERUNNER OF JESUS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>27", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Follow me and leave the dead to bury their own dead\" <br/> By this statement, Jesus means that </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">disciples shall not attend burials</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">there is no life after death</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">following Him comes before anything else</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">disciples shall leave their families in God's care</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement \"Follow me and leave the dead to bury their own dead\" by Jesus means that following Him comes before anything else. In this context, 'the dead' refers to those who are spiritually dead or those who do not follow the teachings of Jesus. Therefore, Jesus is emphasizing the importance of prioritizing spiritual matters over worldly matters.</div>", "topic": "DISCIPLESHIP : THE DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>28", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The disciples became terrified when they saw Jesus walking on the sea because</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they thought He would drown</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they thought He was a ghost</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they lacked faith Him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">there was a great storm</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The disciples became terrified when they saw Jesus walking on the sea because they thought He was a ghost. In the biblical account, when the disciples saw Jesus walking on the water, they were frightened because they thought they were seeing a ghost. Their fear was not due to a lack of faith or the presence of a storm, but rather their misunderstanding of what they were witnessing.</div>", "topic": "MIRACLES : NATURE MIRACLES"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>29", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Jews sought to kill Jesus after He healed the man at the pool of Bethzatha because they thought that He</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">claimed to have authority to forgive sins </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">made Himself equal with God </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">did not agree with the law of Moses</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">said that He was born before Abraham</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In John 5:18, it is stated that the Jews sought to kill Jesus because He not only broke the Sabbath, but also was calling God His own Father, making Himself equal with God.</div>", "topic": "JESUS' TEACHINGS ABOUT HIMSELF : THE LIGHT OF THE WORLD"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>30", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the parable of the sower, the seed that fell among the thorns symbolized the one who hears the word but </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">does not understand it</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">loses it to the enemy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">does not immediately receive it</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the cares of the world choke it </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the parable of the sower, as explained in Matthew 13:22, the seed that fell among the thorns represents the one who hears the word, but the worries of this life and the deceitfulness of wealth choke the word, making it unfruitful.</div>", "topic": "THE PARABLES : PARABLES ABOUT LOVE OF GOD"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>31", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jesus encouraged His followers to rejoice when they were persecuted because</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">great would be their reward in heaven</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">angels would come to their aid</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they would not lack anything good</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">all their sins would be forgiven</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Sermon on the Mount, Jesus said, 'Blessed are those who are persecuted because of righteousness, for theirs is the kingdom of heaven. Rejoice and be glad, because great is your reward in heaven, for in the same way they persecuted the prophets who were before you.' (Matthew 5:10-12). This means that Jesus encouraged His followers to rejoice when they were persecuted because great would be their reward in heaven.</div>", "topic": "INTERPERSONAL RELATIONSHIPS : CHRISTIAN ATTITUDE TO PERSECUTION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>32", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Blessed are you, Simon Bar-Jona! For flesh and blood has not revealed this to you...\" <br/>  As exemplified by the statement above, for believers to be able to identify with Jesus, they must </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">offer their lives</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be led by the Spirit</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">keep all the commandments</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">vow not to deny Him</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement was made by Jesus to Peter after Peter confessed that Jesus was the Christ, the Son of the living God. Jesus told Peter that this revelation was not from flesh and blood, but from His Father in heaven. This implies that for believers to truly identify with Jesus, they must be led by the Spirit of God, as it is the Spirit that reveals the truth about Jesus.</div>", "topic": "THE GREAT CONFESSION : THE SIGNIFICANCE OF THE GREAT CONFESSION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>33", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jesus drove the money changers and sellers of doves out of the Temple because </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the people defiled it with dubious business</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">there was no need for animal sacrifice anymore</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the people wee disobedient to the Law</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">animals and birds were not allowed in it</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jesus drove the money changers and sellers of doves out of the Temple because they were defiling it with their business activities. This is recorded in the Bible in Matthew 21:12-13, where Jesus says, 'My house will be called a house of prayer, but you are making it a den of robbers.' This indicates that the Temple, which was supposed to be a place of worship, had been turned into a place of commerce, hence defiling it.</div>", "topic": "THE TRIUMPHAL ENTRY AND THE CLEANSING OF THE TEMPLE : TRIUMPHAL ENTRY AND THE CLEANSING OF THE TEMPLE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>34", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The tearing of the curtain of the Temple into two at the death of Jesus signifies</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the passing away of the prophets</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">direct access to God through Christ </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">that Jesus was a powerful person </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">that God was truly with Jesus</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The tearing of the curtain of the Temple into two at the death of Jesus signifies direct access to God through Christ. This is recorded in the Bible in Matthew 27:51. Before Jesus' death, the curtain in the Temple separated the Holy of Holies, where God's presence was believed to be, from the rest of the Temple, and only the high priest could enter it once a year. When Jesus died, the curtain was torn, symbolizing that through Jesus' sacrifice, everyone could now have direct access to God, not just the high priest.</div>", "topic": "THE TRIALS AND THE DEATH OF JESUS : CRUCIFIXION AND BURIAL OF JESUS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>35", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Tell people, His disciples came by night and stole him away while we were asleep...\" ' <br/> The intention of the speaker in the statement above was to </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">implicate the disciples</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">absolute the soldiers from all blame</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">deny the resurrection story</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">convince the authority</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The speaker in the statement is trying to deny the resurrection story. The resurrection story is a fundamental belief in Christianity that Jesus Christ was raised from the dead three days after his crucifixion. By saying that the disciples stole Jesus' body while the guards were asleep, the speaker is trying to provide an alternative explanation to the resurrection, thus denying it.</div>", "topic": "RESURRECTION, APPEARANCES AND ASCENSION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION AND APPEARANCE OF JESUS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>36", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jesus charged His followers to walk in the light while they had the light so that they may</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">have eternal life</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">become custodians of it </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">have the light of life</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">become sons of it</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jesus' statement about walking in the light is a metaphor for following his teachings and living a righteous life. When he says 'so that they may have the light of life', he means that by following his teachings (walking in the light), his followers will gain spiritual enlightenment and guidance (the light of life). This is a common theme in Christian teachings, where light is often used as a symbol for goodness, knowledge, and divine presence.</div>", "topic": "JESUS' TEACHINGS ABOUT HIMSELF : THE LIGHT OF THE WORLD"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>37", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the early Church, believers devoted themselves to the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">daily distribution of food </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">apostles' teaching and fellowship</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">breaking of bread in the Temple</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">performance of miracles</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the early Church, believers devoted themselves to the apostles' teaching and fellowship. This is recorded in the book of Acts 2:42, where it is stated that they devoted themselves to the apostles' teaching and to fellowship, to the breaking of bread and to prayer.</div>", "topic": "FELLOWSHIP IN THE EARLY CHURCH : COMMUNAL LIVING"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>38", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The disciple that went to preach in Samaria after the great persecution in Jerusalem was</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Philip</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Andrew</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Peter</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">James</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">After the great persecution in Jerusalem, it was Philip who went to preach in Samaria. This is recorded in Acts 8:5, where it is stated that Philip went down to a city in Samaria and proclaimed the Messiah there.</div>", "topic": "MISSION TO THE GENTILES : THE COMMISSIONING AND MISSION OF PAUL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>39", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Saul was converted so that he might </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">cause confusion among the Jews</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">help Peter in his work</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">not be killed for his sins </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">spread the word to the Gentiles</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Saul, who later became known as Paul, was converted on the road to Damascus. After his conversion, he became one of the most fervent apostles of Christianity, spreading the word to the Gentiles. This is recorded in the book of Acts in the Bible.</div>", "topic": "MISSION TO THE GENTILES : CONVERSION OF SAUL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>40", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">What effect did the decision of the Council of Jerusalem have on the early church?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Members became more united </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Church experienced freedom from persecution</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Jews became leaders of the community </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Gentiles were free to be members of the Church</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Council of Jerusalem, as described in Acts 15, was a meeting of the early Christian community to resolve the issue of whether Gentiles who converted to Christianity needed to follow Jewish customs and laws. The decision was that they did not, which helped to unify the early church as it meant that Gentiles and Jews could worship together without the need for Gentiles to adopt Jewish customs. This decision helped to unify the members of the early church.</div>", "topic": "MISSION TO THE GENTILES : THE COUNCIL OF JERUSALEM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>41", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Paul in Romans stated that the righteousness of God has been manifested through</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the Law</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the priests</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">faith in Jesus</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Temple sacrifices</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Romans, specifically Romans 3:21-22, Paul states that the righteousness of God has been manifested through faith in Jesus Christ for all who believe. Therefore, the correct answer is 'faith in Jesus'.</div>", "topic": "THE LAW AND GRACE : THE PURPOSE AND SIGNIFICANCE OF THE LAW AND GRACE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>42", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Romans, all who were also baptized into His </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">crucifixion</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">persecution</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">suffering</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">death</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Romans 6:3, Paul states that all of us who were baptized into Christ Jesus were baptized into his death. Therefore, the correct answer is 'death'.</div>", "topic": "NEW LIFE IN CHRIST : CONDITIONS AND BENEFITS OF NEW LIFE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>43", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Paul in Philippians, humility means giving consideration to other people's</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wealth </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">weakness</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">interests</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">needs</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Philippians 2:4, Paul instructs, 'Let each of you look not only to his own interests, but also to the interests of others.' This verse implies that humility involves considering the interests of others, not just one's own.</div>", "topic": "HUMILITY : MEANING AND REQUIREMENTS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>44", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Corinthians, believers are taught to forgive one another in order to </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">keep Satan from gaining advantage</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">prevent the wrong doer from losing his salvation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">remove the curse from the offender</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">discourage the offender from committing more sin</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In 2 Corinthians 2:10-11, Paul writes, 'Anyone you forgive, I also forgive. And what I have forgiven—if there was anything to forgive—I have forgiven in the sight of Christ for your sake, in order that Satan might not outwit us. For we are not unaware of his schemes.' This suggests that forgiveness is necessary to prevent Satan from gaining an advantage over believers.</div>", "topic": "FORGIVENESS : PAUL’S TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>45", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Corinthians, Paul stated that by one Spirit we were</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">free from bondage of sin</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">united into one church</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">committed to Christian service</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">baptized into one body</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In 1 Corinthians 12:13, Paul stated that 'For by one Spirit we were all baptized into one body'. This means that through the Holy Spirit, all believers become part of the body of Christ, which is the church. Therefore, the correct answer is 'baptized into one body'.</div>", "topic": "CHRISTIANS AS JOINT HEIRS WITH CHRIST : HOW CHRISTIANS ARE JOINT HEIRS WITH CHRIST"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>46", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Paul commended the churches in Macedonia for giving out of their freewill to the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">saints</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">poor </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">priests</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sick</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In 2 Corinthians 8:1-5, Paul commended the churches in Macedonia for their generosity in giving out of their own free will, despite their own poverty, to the saints in Jerusalem. Therefore, the correct answer is 'saints'.</div>", "topic": "CHRISTIAN GIVING : THE IMPORTANCE OF CHRISTIAN GIVING"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>47", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"Pay all of them their dues, taxes to whom taxes are due, revenue to whom revenue is due, respect to whom respect is due, honour to whom honour is due.\"nl*Paul made the statement above to the Church at</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Thessalonica</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Rome</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Corinth</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ephesus</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement \"Pay all of them their dues, taxes to whom taxes are due, revenue to whom revenue is due, respect to whom respect is due, honour to whom honour is due.\" was made by Paul in his letter to the Romans. This can be found in Romans 13:7 of the Bible.</div>", "topic": "CIVIC RESPONSIBILITY : THE NEED FOR OBEDIENCE TO AUTHORITY"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>48", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">At the second coming of Christ, those who are alive shall be</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">bound to life</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">caught up together with the lord</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">separated from the dead</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">taken to the new Jerusalem</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to 1 Thessalonians 4:17 in the Bible, at the second coming of Christ, those who are alive and remain shall be caught up together with them in the clouds to meet the Lord in the air. Therefore, the correct answer is 'caught up together with the lord'.</div>", "topic": "THE SECOND COMING OF CHRIST : PREPARATION FOR HIS COMING"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>49", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to James, treatment of brethren at fellowship should not be based on </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">appearance </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sentiments</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">gender</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">age</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of James, it is stated that believers should not show favoritism based on appearance. James 2:1-4 warns against favoritism, stating that if a man with gold rings and fine clothes comes into your assembly, and a poor man in shabby clothing also comes in, and you pay attention to the one who wears the fine clothing and say, 'You sit here in a good place,' while you say to the poor man, 'You stand over there,' or, 'Sit down at my feet,' have you not then made distinctions among yourselves and become judges with evil thoughts? This clearly indicates that treatment of brethren at fellowship should not be based on appearance.</div>", "topic": "IMPARTIALITY : CONCEPT OF IMPARTIALITY"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2011>50", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Peter in his epistle, charged his fellow elders to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">take care of their families</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be strong in their faith </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">have compassion on the weak</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">tend the flock of God</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In 1 Peter 5:1-2, Peter charges his fellow elders to 'tend the flock of God that is in your charge, exercising the oversight, not under compulsion but willingly, as God would have you do it—not for sordid gain but eagerly.' This clearly indicates that Peter charged his fellow elders to tend the flock of God.</div>", "topic": "LEADERSHIP QUALITIES : PASTORAL CARE"}];
